data.title: Carlos Moya (Spain)
data.meta_description: He may not ooze the consistency that took him to the world number one rank in 1999 anymore, but Carlos Moya remains a serious threat.
data.text:
ByEurosport

Published 09/11/2004 at 07:35 GMT

Carlos Moya may not ooze the consistency that took him to the world number one ranking in 1999 anymore, but the Spaniard is still a danger on all surfaces. A winner of three tour titles this season, the 28-year-old has helped his country to the Davis Cup

Born: 27 August 1976, Palma de Mallorca

Residence: Geneva, Switzerland

Professional Since: 1995

HOUSTON PROFILES

Roger Federer (Switzerland)

13/11/2004 at 06:48

Career Singles titles: 17

Singles Titles in 2004: Three – Chennai, Acapulco, Rome Masters

MAJOR CHAMPIONSHIP RECORD 2004

Australian Open – Did Not Play; Roland Garros – QF (lost to Guillermo Coria); Wimbledon – 4R (lost to Lleyton Hewitt); U.S. Open – 3R (lost to Olivier Rochus)

BIOGRAPHY

Carlos Moya qualified for the Masters Cup in fifth place on the back of consistent performances throughout the season.

Three titles came the Spaniard's way in Chennai, Acapulco and the Rome Masters from five finals (runner-up in Sydney and Buenos Aires) with quarter and semi-final displays in seven other tournaments.

The drive and determination that took Moya to the number one ranking in March 1999 may have been dimmed by injury, but the 28-year-old is still a mighty force.

An injury sustained during Spain's Davis Cup semi-final victory over France in September saw him skip Madrid and Paris Masters events.

Only a lack of match practice will prevent Moya from adding to his 56-17 season win-loss record in Houston.
